## üß© ARTICLE VIII: STANDARDS FOR MODULAR EXPANSION
‚Ä¢	Section 8.01: Factor Isolation: Every new factor must possess its own dedicated ingestion (01_ingest_...) and transformation (02_trans_...) script to prevent cross-contamination and maintain a clean audit trail5.
‚Ä¢	Section 8.02: The Equalization Rule: Metrics must be population-weighted at the MSA level6. This ensures that the "Jacksonville Metro" score is a true aggregate and is not skewed by outlier data from a single high-population county like Duval.
‚Ä¢	Section 8.03: Cross-Factor Correlation: Upon the completion of two or more factors, the system shall trigger a Synthesis Agent. This agent‚Äôs mandate is to analyze inter-factor interactions (e.g., "How does Labor Vitality (Factor 03) impact Household Stress (Factor 01)?").
________________________________________
## ü§ñ ARTICLE IX: PHASING OF AGENTIC DEPTH
Expansion is defined not merely by data volume, but by "Intellectual Maturity." Agents must be deployed in the following strict chronological order7:
Phase 1: The Explainer (Current)
‚Ä¢	Mandate: Translates deterministic data into plain-English, human-economist summaries8888.
‚Ä¢	Constraint: Must not "think" or hallucinate; it strictly explains results9.
Phase 2: The Skeptic (Skeptical Economist)
‚Ä¢	Mandate: Designed to challenge the Explainer's findings, identify statistical anomalies, and mitigate AI hallucinations10101010.
Phase 3: The Sentinel (Alert Agent)
‚Ä¢	Mandate: An automated monitoring agent that triggers notifications when a material economic change (e.g., a >5% shift in a metric) is detected11.
Phase 4: The Strategist (Scenario Agent)
‚Ä¢	Mandate: Conducts "What if?" modeling to forecast impacts (e.g., "If interest rates drop 1%, what is the projected impact on Housing Health?")12.
